{
  "answer": "**The opening couplet (matla, or first sher) of Mirza Ghalib's ghazal \"Koi ummeed bar nahin aati\" (Chapter 115 in *Diwan-E-Ghalib*) is the most famous for its line on hopelessness.**[^1]\n\nThis couplet sets the tone for the entire ghazal, which revolves around the refrain *nahin aati* (\"does not come\"), expressing despair over hope (*ummeed*), vision (*soorat nazar*), sleep (*neend*), laughter (*hansi*), piety (*ta'at o zohd*), speech (*baat*), remembrance (*yaad*), healing (*chaara*), news (*khabar*), death (*maut*), and even shame (*sharm*). The first line—\"Koi ummeed bar nahin aati\" (in transliteration)—directly embodies hopelessness and is the ghazal's iconic signature.[^2]\n\n> Koi ummeed bar nahin aati  \n> Koi soorat nazar nahin aati  \n> \n> *No hope I have is ever answered,*  \n> *No way ahead can be uncovered.*[^1]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [p-92c600](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/115-koi-ummeed-bar-nahin-aati/translation/#p-92c600).\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [Chapter 115](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/115-koi-ummeed-bar-nahin-aati/translation/).",
